description: {"blocks":[{"key":"4mkg8","text":"Timely submission of viral sequence and corresponding contextual data by public health laboratories is an essential step to SARS-CoV-2 biosurveillance. This enables real-time updating of repositories of sequence data, hence real-time tracking of information on the virus as gathered from the sequence data and metadata as well. There are various sequence repositories or databases (with a section dedicated to SARS-CoV-2 viral sequences) that are publicly-available online, such as GISAID and the INSDC repositories. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ahis4","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"8me37","text":"The previous project involved submission of the sequences generated by the PGC Mindanao workflow to the GISAID database. In collaboration with BugSeq on the PHA4GE subgrant, PGC Mindanao was also able to upload and submit the previously-generated SARS-CoV-2 sequences to NCBI, a database that is part of the INSDC, which in turn subsequently released these sequences to its public database successfully.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"8jp79","text":"PGC Mindanao workflow","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":21}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4qc12","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"5l77b","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"bc9ch","text":"This section outlines the PGC Mindanao workflow for the submission of sequence and contextual data to a public database. Figure 1 shows an overview of the entire workflow. The workflow ultimately deposits the sequence and contextual data to the online public database GISAID.  ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"eq4jg","text":" ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ftqbd","text":"     ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"7996n","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7qk0i","text":"After assembling and generating the consensus sequences from the viral samples, the sequences are assessed and filtered for the number of ambiguous bases and presence of frameshift mutations and unexpected stop codons in the sequences as confirmed by the sequencing data and not from sequencing artifacts. Sequencing having less than 50% ambiguous bases and have frameshift mutations and unexpected stop codons that are confirmed by the sequencing data will be included in the GISAID submission and those otherwise were not included (refer to Section 2.6 - \"Nextclade workflow\" of the protocol \"Introduction and Lineage Assignment of Assembled Sequences\" for details). The headers of the multi-sequence FASTA files were renamed conforming to GISAID requirements (Section 2.1). Parallel to this, sequence metadata were also uploaded to REDCap according to the appropriate data access group of each Sub-National Laboratory (SNL) (Section 2.2).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":1,"offset":595,"length":58}],"data":{}},{"key":"cbst","text":"","type":"align-justify","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"8s76b","text":"Sequences were uploaded to REDCap using the script provided by the previous project (succeeding steps were also performed with scripts provided by the previous project). Similar to the metadata, the sequence data were uploaded to REDCap according to the appropriate data access group of each SNL. Both sequence data and metadata were scraped from the REDCap database using the provided Python script (Section 2.2). PGC Mindanao verified the sequences and the corresponding metadata. When verification was done, the sequences and the metadata were uploaded to GISAID through their submission protocol (Section 2.3).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"biu6e","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"fd56o","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"t7cs","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"image","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"guid":"4AA812F066EB11EDB0523D4FE6EE29D1","height":733,"id":329926,"is_video":false,"legend":{"blocks":[{"data":{},"depth":0,"entityRanges":[],"inlineStyleRanges":[],"key":"ftetl","text":"Figure 1. {"blocks":[{"key":"7vj1j","text":"Submission to GISAID database:","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6kelf","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4egv0","text":"The spreadsheet outputted by \"gisaidprep.py\" (containing the sequence metadata) from the previous section, along with the final formatted sequence FASTA file, will be used for uploading the sequence data and metadata to GISAID. Figure 7 shows the spreadsheet outputted by \"gisaidprep.py\" metadata that will be submitted to GISAID in conjunction with the sequence data. Standard GISAID submission procedure was performed, wherein the recommended approach is through the use of the command-line tool CLI2. This process requires a live client ID for authentication, which may be requested by emailing the support team for this tool at GISAID (clisupport@gisaid.org). Figure 8 shows a number of the commands that can be issued by the CLI2 command-line tool.","type":"align-justify","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"1mqu","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"2md5","text":"","type":"align-justify","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6u93l","text":"  ","type":"align-justify","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"3f1ls","text":"","type":"align-justify","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"11c7e","text":"","type":"align-justify","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"5dksv","text":"  ","type":"align-justify","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":1,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"bo8s5","text":"After submission of the sequence data and metadata to GISAID through the CLI2 tool, the data will be reviewed by curators at GISAID. The uploader will be notified by email of successfully-released samples (together with their corresponding individual accession IDs) from submit@gisaid.org, and the samples made immediately available to registered GISAID users. On the other hand, the uploader will be notified by email of unsuccessful sample/s from hcov-19@gisaid.org with the reason for the non-release of each of these sample/s. The uploader may resubmit with the corrected sequence/s or inform GISAID that the sequence/s is correct and is supported by the raw sequencing data.
